As a number theorist, I can tell you the range of this function is fundamentally tied to the nature of squares and square roots.  

Since squaring any real number yields a non-negative result, the input to the square root function will always be non-negative. Consequently, the output of the square root will also always be non-negative.  

Therefore, the range of the function $f(x) = \sqrt{x^2}$ is the set of all non-negative real numbers.

